# Definition of Done

## Purpose

This document defines the minimum quality requirements that must be satisfied before work is considered complete in {{ project_name }}.

Completing an implementation is not enough. Every change should also be verified, documented, and maintainable.

## General requirements

A completed change should:

* implement the intended behavior
* include appropriate tests where practical
* pass the full quality pipeline
* avoid introducing regressions
* update documentation when required
* be reviewed before merging

## Project structure

The repository should maintain the expected structure:

* `src/`
* `tests/`
* `docs/`
* `README.md`
* `LICENSE`
* `CHANGELOG.md`
* `CONTRIBUTING.md`
* `pyproject.toml`

## Code quality

Every completed change must pass:

```bash
just check
```

This validates:

* Ruff linting
* Ruff formatting
* Basedpyright static analysis
* Pytest

No warnings or errors should be ignored without documented justification.

## Testing

Completed work should:

* include tests for new behavior where practical
* preserve existing passing tests
* avoid flaky or order-dependent tests
* avoid unnecessary external dependencies in unit tests

Regression fixes should include a regression test whenever reasonable.

## Packaging

The project must:

* install successfully using `uv sync`
* build successfully using Hatchling
* keep `uv.lock` committed and current
* maintain a valid package structure under:

```text
src/{{ package_name }}/
```

## Documentation

Documentation should be updated whenever changes affect:

* setup
* development workflow
* commands
* configuration
* architecture
* public behavior

Architecture decisions should be recorded as ADRs when appropriate.

## Version control

Before merging:

* commits should be atomic
* commit messages should be descriptive
* unrelated changes should not be mixed together
* generated artifacts should not be committed

The working tree should be clean after validation.

## Continuous Integration

The CI pipeline must succeed before changes are merged.

Local validation and CI should use equivalent commands to minimize environment-specific failures.

## Security

Completed work must not:

* expose secrets
* reduce dependency security without justification
* introduce unnecessary permissions
* weaken validation without documentation

Sensitive information must never be committed to the repository.

## Maintainability

New code should:

* follow the documented development standards
* integrate naturally with the existing project structure
* avoid unnecessary complexity
* remain understandable to another engineer without relying on chat history

## Completion checklist

A change is considered complete when:

* [ ] Implementation is finished
* [ ] Tests have been added or updated where appropriate
* [ ] `just check` passes
* [ ] Documentation has been updated where required
* [ ] The Git diff has been reviewed
* [ ] The commit is focused and descriptive
* [ ] CI passes after pushing
